Beekman Street, at, adjoining and east of the N.E. corner of Gold Street. Shown at the corner proper (No. 64), is the "Old Beekman" erected in 1827.

About 1910.

(1)
Gold Street, at, adjoining and north from the N.E. corner of Beekman Street. Also shown is Nos. 64-68 Beekman Street, at and adjoining the N.E. corner of Gold Street. Note the "Old Beekman" erected in 1827, at the corner proper.
May 7, 1929.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
The same.
May 1923.

(1)
Beekman Street, west from and including Gold Street to Park Row, showing at the latter point the domed United States Post Office, in the southern tip of City Hall Park. In the background is the huge Woolworth Building.

July 26, 1930.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
The same, emphasizing the north side. The structure bearing the sign "Pies - Sandwiches" is No. 64 Beekman Street at the N.E. corner of Gold Street and called the "Old Beekman." It was erected in 1827. For further views of same, see Gold Street.

May 2, 1932.

P. L. Sperr.
